You need to find the intersection point of two lines, $AB$ and $CD.$
I know that the general form of a line in 3D (\textit{Cartesian} coordinates) is $\mathscr{L}(a, b, c)$, where
\begin{equation*}
\mathscr{L}=\{(x, y, z) = a+b\mathbb{s}+c\mathbb{t}:\, \mathbb{s}, \mathbb{t}\in\mathbb{R}\}.
\end{equation*}
For $A=(-2,\,3,\,5)$ and $B=(7,\,0,\,-1),$
\begin{equation}A+B=(-2+7,\,3+0,\,5-1)=\big(\,5,\,3,\,4\,\big),
\end{equation}
and
\begin{equation*}
B-A=(7-(-2),\,0-3,\,-1-5)=(9,\,-3,\,-6)
\end{equation*}
That gives
$\begin{aligned}
A+B+x(B-A) &= \mathscr{L}(\lambda,\,\mu)\\
(5,\,3,\,4)+x(9,\,-3,\,-6) &= \mathscr{L}(\lambda,\,\mu)\\
5+9x &=  \lambda\\
3+(-3x) &= \mu\\
4-6x &= \mathscr{L}
\end{aligned}$
So you need to solve the following system of three equations in $\lambda,\,\mu,$ and $x$: 
\begin{equation}
\begin{cases}
5+9x = \lambda\\
3-3x = \mu\\
4-6x = \lambda
\end{cases}
\end{equation}
But I will not talk about this system now, since $\lambda$ appears twice in the system. We can remove it, by eliminating it.
Let us solve the first one first to solve $x$:
\begin{equation*}
\lambda=5+9x
\end{equation*}
Substituting this into the third one, we get
$\begin{aligned}
\Big(\,5+9x\,\Big)-6x &= 4\\
5+9x -6x &= 4\\
3x &= -1\\
x &=-\dfrac{1}{3}
\end{aligned}$
If $x=-\dfrac{1}{3},$
\begin{equation*}
\lambda=\Bigg(\,5+9\Big(-\dfrac{1}{3}\Big)\Bigg)=2
\end{equation*}
We have $\lambda=2.$
\begin{equation*}
\mu=3-3\Big(-\dfrac{1}{3}\Big)=\color{royalblue}{4}
\end{equation*}
So we have found the point of intersection of $\mathscr{L}_1$ and $\mathscr{L}_2$ ($\Big(\,5+9\Big(-\dfrac{1}{3}\Big)\Big),\,3-3\Big(-\dfrac{1}{3}\Big),\,4-6\Big(-\dfrac{1}{3}\Big)\Big)$ is $\Big(\,2,\,4,\,6\,\Big).$</answer>

